They weren't merely walking along the tracks (which happens all the
time); they were actually playing in the trackbed.  On a very busy
railroad, trains unpredictably running in both directions on both
tracks.  In front of a curve.  (The bi-directional running scarse me
because trespassing think they are watching the track in front of
them, not realizing a train could sneak up behind them.  Or, people
think just because a train passed there won't be another along for a
while.  Not true here.)

Yes, I felt it was dangerous in that location because of the above.
Also, sometimes when people are faced with an oncoming train they
freeze up rather than move.  Or, their foot gets stuck under a rail or
they trip while running.

We have had nasty accidents on other lines.  Of course, the parents
blame the lack of fencing, even though it's the kids who cut through
it.

As to talking to the kids directly instead of the cops, the kids were
too far away (I was at ths station).  I called the cops, and the cop
himself went down the tracks to get the kids.  So, there wasn't any
issue of me needing to identify the kids, the cop found them in the
trackbed himself.  It turned out the kids were rather young.

For the future, I will defnitely not the my neighbors afterward.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> But realistically, how many of us here have _never_ trespassed on
> railroad property, especially when we were kids?
">

I knew a kid in high school killed while doing that.  I was also on (a
psgr) a train that hit a trespassing kid.

I asked a neighbor if the schools around here give safety training.
We had it.  I was told no, they don't.

Thanks to all for their responses.
